{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":689,"record_hash":"sha256:bc8b798852192dd96200adbc7f6ef33465e42752844e42565c8cc75d08b04d2e","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:10:23.657Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 71154a\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1023\nOutput:\nV1 behavior:\n\n- host the product in Forge, outside the GitButler repository\n- support public GitHub repositories only; private repositories are out of\n  scope for the MVP\n- do not support fork pull requests\n- fetch only `refs/meta/main` from the public repository resolved from the PR URL\n- treat publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` as already published public metadata\n- use `but-agentlog` to interpret GitButler agentlog data\n- query both the PR review target and the PR head branch\n- rank review-target matches above branch-only matches\n- render a generated snapshot page with overview plus session/turn drill-down\n- serve the stable PR route as the user-facing route; keep immutable snapshot\n  ids internal for v1\n\nSnapshot identity:\n\n```text\nforge_host + owner + repo + pr_number + metadata_ref_oid + selected_session_turn_keys\n```\n\nSession and turn keys should be deduped and sorted before deriving a stable\nsnapshot id.\n\n## Entry Point\n\nThe first entry point is on-demand URL replacement from an existing GitHub pull\nrequest URL.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nhttps://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n```\n\nA user could replace `github.com` with a GitButler-owned Agent Trail domain and\nland on a derived review page for the same pull request.\n\nConceptually:\n\n```text\nhttps://agent-trail.gitbutler.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n```\n\nThe backend would parse the forge URL shape, resolve the repository and pull\nrequest, check whether it has access, then build or load the Agent Trail\noverview for that PR.\n\nAccept only canonical GitHub pull request route shapes. Strip query strings,\nhashes, and trailing slashes. Do not accept arbitrary git URLs or fetch remotes\nderived from unchecked user input.\n\nFor GitHub PRs, the pull request number should map to the `but-agentlog`\n`review` target. For example, PR `13936` should query the review target value\n`13936`, which `but-agentlog` normalizes to the stored key:\n\n```text\ngi\n[TRUNCATED]\nuse `but-agentlog` target constructors or query APIs once those exist,\nnot hand-roll GitButler agentlog key normalization.\n\nThis review target is optional because captured metadata may not always include\nreview information. When it is present, it is the strongest first lookup for a\nPR-scoped Agent Trail.\n\nThe server can also use the GitHub API to resolve PR metadata, especially the\nhead branch behind the pull request. The canonical v1 flow is:\n\n```text\nparse PR URL -> GitHub PR lookup -> initialize/refresh repo cache\n-> fetch refs/meta/main -> but-agentlog lookup -> snapshot page\n```\n\nThe server should fetch public PR metadata from GitHub, resolve the PR head\nbranch, and search both useful MVP targets in one pass:\n\n```text\nreview target: gitbutler-review:13936\nbranch target: ref:refs/heads/<pr-head-branch>\n```\n\nCurrent preference: search both when PR metadata is already available, then rank\nreview-target hits above branch-only hits. If GitHub PR lookup fails, v1 should\nfail closed with a retryable error state instead of guessing from GitMeta alone.\n\nBranch fallback is useful but weaker. A branch can be reused, renamed, or shared\nacross unrelated work. The UI should show why each session matched and avoid\ntreating branch-only matches as proof that the session belongs to the PR.\nBranch-only matches should be visually separated from review-target matches and\nraw record drill-down for branch-only matches should require an explicit expand.\n\nChange target lookup is not relevant for the MVP. It can be considered later if\nAgent Trail needs a deeper GitButler-specific view of stacked changes.\n\nThe first version should focus on public/open-source repositories. Private\nrepository access, GitHub OAuth, GitButler workspace access, and explicit share\nlinks can come later.\n\nFor public v1, Agent Trail treats a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` as\nalready published metadata. On-demand URL replacement does not grant access to\nprivate data; it only renders a review page from metadata that is fetchable\nwithout credentials.\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:10:23.657Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}